279
00:16:18,294 --> 00:16:20,044
       Narrator: In 1994,       

280
00:16:20,046 --> 00:16:22,263
      fishermen up and down     
      the New England Coast     

281
00:16:22,265 --> 00:16:24,599
    receive stunning news --    

282
00:16:24,601 --> 00:16:26,250
     The fish that have been    
          so plentiful          

283
00:16:26,252 --> 00:16:29,587
      for hundreds of years     
        are disappearing.       

284
00:16:29,589 --> 00:16:33,424
      Species like haddock,     
  flounder, and the mighty cod  

285
00:16:33,426 --> 00:16:36,611
    are in a dangerous state    
           of decline.          

286
00:16:36,613 --> 00:16:39,113
         We discovered,         
     "Wow, we can over-fish     

287
00:16:39,115 --> 00:16:41,566
          just as much          
      as the Russians can."     

288
00:16:41,568 --> 00:16:45,620
         And, you know,         
       bust followed boom.      

289
00:16:45,622 --> 00:16:49,157
   Narrator: To give the fish   
      a chance to rebound,      

290
00:16:49,159 --> 00:16:52,126
      the National Oceanic      
 and Atmospheric Administration,

291
00:16:52,128 --> 00:16:56,781
      NOAA, comes up with a     
 complicated set of regulations.

292
00:16:56,783 --> 00:16:59,450
     This a national crisis.    
        We are trying...        

293
00:16:59,452 --> 00:17:01,002
     Narrator: At the time,     
          John Bullard          

294
00:17:01,004 --> 00:17:03,721
  is the regional administrator 
            of NOAA.            

295
00:17:03,723 --> 00:17:09,093
   And the rules are complex,   
        to say the least.       

296
00:17:09,095 --> 00:17:11,979
 I mean, our rules are literally
           that thick.          

297
00:17:11,981 --> 00:17:13,398
             Woman:             
  <i> So, fisherman, processors...</i> 

298
00:17:13,400 --> 00:17:15,433
            Narrator:           
   The fishermen are furious.   

299
00:17:15,435 --> 00:17:17,185
        They see not only       
        their livelihood,       

300
00:17:17,187 --> 00:17:21,105
    but an entire way of life   
   on the brink of extinction.  

301
00:17:21,107 --> 00:17:23,691
    The new regulations means   
     you're out of business.    

302
00:17:23,693 --> 00:17:25,142
  I'm gonna lose everything --  

303
00:17:25,144 --> 00:17:26,494
   Everything I've worked for   
          for 35 years.         

304
00:17:26,496 --> 00:17:28,579
   It's only a matter of time.  

305
00:17:28,581 --> 00:17:30,815
  We're trying to survive here. 

306
00:17:30,817 --> 00:17:33,317
      Bullard: Think about      
      what kind of a person     

307
00:17:33,319 --> 00:17:36,654
         wants to go out        
     and brave the elements.    

308
00:17:36,656 --> 00:17:39,674
        They're fiercely        
       independent people.      

309
00:17:39,676 --> 00:17:41,626
      They're not the kind      
       of person who says,      

310
00:17:41,628 --> 00:17:43,828
     "Oh, hey, regulate me."    

311
00:17:43,830 --> 00:17:45,346
   I got no money!              

312
00:17:45,348 --> 00:17:47,515
  You and everybody             
  talking, talking!             

313
00:17:47,517 --> 00:17:49,183
   I see no money!              

314
00:17:49,185 --> 00:17:51,302
  Narrator: And while fishermen 
      with small operations     

315
00:17:51,304 --> 00:17:53,054
         are yelling...         
    [Bleep]                     

316
00:17:53,056 --> 00:17:57,692
     ...Carlos Rafael knows     
        he will survive.        

317
00:18:04,200 --> 00:18:07,485
  In Rafael's mind, "the weak"  
  are the hundreds of fishermen 

318
00:18:07,487 --> 00:18:13,241
 who operate one or two boats --
    people like Rodman Sykes.   

319
00:18:13,243 --> 00:18:15,877
            Sykes is            
  a third-generation fisherman  

320
00:18:15,879 --> 00:18:20,164
   operating near New Bedford,  
 in Point Judith, Rhode Island. 

321
00:18:20,166 --> 00:18:22,216
      The only other thing      
       I ever wanted to do      

322
00:18:22,218 --> 00:18:23,835
      was play second base      
        for the Red Sox,        

323
00:18:23,837 --> 00:18:25,419
 and that didn't work out, so...

324
00:18:25,421 --> 00:18:28,372
           [ Laughs ]           
    So I became a fisherman.    

325
00:18:28,374 --> 00:18:31,559
     Narrator: Sykes begins     
       his fishing career       

326
00:18:31,561 --> 00:18:34,645
        at the same time        
  Rafael enters the industry -- 

327
00:18:34,647 --> 00:18:36,564
      in the good ol' days.     

328
00:18:36,566 --> 00:18:38,766
 Sykes: Back then, you could do 
   whatever you wanted to do.   

329
00:18:38,768 --> 00:18:40,101
 I mean, you throw the lines off

330
00:18:40,103 --> 00:18:41,736
         and go fishing         
      whenever you wanted,      

331
00:18:41,738 --> 00:18:43,905
   catch whatever you wanted.   

332
00:18:43,907 --> 00:18:46,357
 Narrator: But then he is faced 
        with regulations        

333
00:18:46,359 --> 00:18:49,076
    that limit the horsepower   
           on his boat          

334
00:18:49,078 --> 00:18:52,062
  and dictate that he use nets  
         with wider mesh        

335
00:18:52,064 --> 00:18:55,065
     to decrease his catch.     

336
00:18:55,067 --> 00:18:59,871
    It was just going from no   
 restrictions to that was scary.

337
00:18:59,873 --> 00:19:01,238
  You know, you're hauling net, 

338
00:19:01,240 --> 00:19:02,790
           and you see          
   these great, big flounders   

339
00:19:02,792 --> 00:19:04,125
        swimming on right       
        through the mesh,       

340
00:19:04,127 --> 00:19:05,743
     just go, swimming away.    

341
00:19:05,745 --> 00:19:08,045
             I said,            
  "We can't possibly do this."  

342
00:19:08,047 --> 00:19:12,700
  Narrator: But the most severe 
 restriction for some fishermen 

343
00:19:12,702 --> 00:19:17,889
  is a limitation on the number 
  of days a boat can be at sea. 

344
00:19:17,891 --> 00:19:21,091
     Over time, as the fish     
         don't rebound,         

345
00:19:21,093 --> 00:19:26,063
       the number of days       
    gets smaller and smaller.   

346
00:19:26,065 --> 00:19:28,316
    Bullard: If someone says,   

347
00:19:28,318 --> 00:19:32,787
 "I'm going to reduce the number
     of days you can fish,"     

348
00:19:32,789 --> 00:19:34,739
  that hits the family budget.  

349
00:19:34,741 --> 00:19:36,157
     That has consequences.     

350
00:19:36,159 --> 00:19:40,077
          That may mean         
     that the captain says,     

351
00:19:40,079 --> 00:19:42,463
          "Sorry, guys,         
     we're not gonna be able    

352
00:19:42,465 --> 00:19:44,415
  to provide health insurance," 

353
00:19:44,417 --> 00:19:50,338
         in the nation's        
       most dangerous job.      

354
00:19:50,340 --> 00:19:53,007
  Narrator: And that means that 
     thousands of fishermen     

355
00:19:53,009 --> 00:19:55,476
 are forced out of the business.

356
00:19:57,647 --> 00:20:00,748
 But Carlos Rafael is thriving. 

357
00:20:00,750 --> 00:20:03,100
   He has added scallop boats   
          to his fleet,         

358
00:20:03,102 --> 00:20:07,137
   and they more than make up   
  for the losses in groundfish. 

359
00:20:07,139 --> 00:20:10,474
     He was doing quite fine    
     running his scallopers,    

360
00:20:10,476 --> 00:20:11,859
       no doubt about it,       

361
00:20:11,861 --> 00:20:15,696
       and making millions      
    and millions of dollars.    

362
00:20:15,698 --> 00:20:18,115
 Narrator: And, as for all those
      rules and regulations     

363
00:20:18,117 --> 00:20:20,451
     to protect groundfish?     

364
00:20:20,453 --> 00:20:21,786
              Easy.             

365
00:20:21,788 --> 00:20:24,705
      It appears he simply      
          ignores them.         

366
00:20:24,707 --> 00:20:27,124
 I don't think that he actively 
      sought to break them.     

367
00:20:27,126 --> 00:20:29,377
         They just were         
       meaningless to him.      

368
00:20:29,379 --> 00:20:31,545
       "I'm just gonna do       
       what I want to do,       

369
00:20:31,547 --> 00:20:35,332
    because I want to do it."   

370
00:20:35,334 --> 00:20:39,787
    Narrator: And, over time,   
     violations stack up --     

371
00:20:39,789 --> 00:20:44,642
     exceeded haddock limit,    
     fished in closed area,     

372
00:20:44,644 --> 00:20:47,344
   exceeded days at sea limit,  

373
00:20:47,346 --> 00:20:50,698
         submitted false        
      daily-catch reports.      

374
00:20:50,700 --> 00:20:53,000
    But, as he tells the IRS,   

375
00:20:53,002 --> 00:20:56,537
      he is not intimidated     
    by government inspectors.   

376
00:21:07,717 --> 00:21:09,533
            Bullard:            
       He's incorrigible.       

377
00:21:09,535 --> 00:21:14,722
    This is his way of life,    
   to break the law repeatedly  

378
00:21:14,724 --> 00:21:17,041
          and challenge         
     the federal government     

379
00:21:17,043 --> 00:21:18,559
          to catch him          

380
00:21:18,561 --> 00:21:23,681
    and then catch him again    
    and then catch him again.   

381
00:21:23,683 --> 00:21:26,267
    Narrator: And the feds<i> do</i>   
     continue to catch him.     

382
